data: {"type":"response.reasoning_summary_part.done","item_id":"rs_05b3f9e989ad3802016a048ca8e0b88193945710ade8f8cd1c","output_index":0,"part":{"type":"summary_text","text":"**Calculating meeting time and distance**\n\nI'm looking at the relative speed of 180 km/h. To find the time, I use the formula: time equals distance divided by speed. So, 390 km divided by 180 km/h gives me 13/6 hours, which is 2 hours and 10 minutes. They meet at 6:10 pm. The distance from Paris can be calculated as 80 times (1 plus 13/6), or simply using 80 times 3 and 1/6, which also gives me 253 1/3 km. I’ll provide units for clarity."},"sequence_number":222,"summary_index":1}

event: response.output_item.done
data: {"type":"response.output_item.done","item":{"id":"rs_05b3f9e989ad3802016a048ca8e0b88193945710ade8f8cd1c","type":"reasoning","summary":[{"type":"summary_text","text":"**Calculating distance of Train A**\n\nTrain A travels from 3 pm to 6:10 pm, which is 3 hours and 10 minutes or 3.1667 hours at a speed of 80 km/h. To find the distance, I multiply the time by the speed: 80 km/h times 3.1667 gives me 253.333 km. I could break it down further, showing how 3 hours plus 10 minutes equals 190 minutes, which is also 3.1667 hours. So I conclude that Train A meets at 6:10 pm, 253 1/3 km from Paris."},{"type":"summary_text","text":"**Calculating meeting time and distance**\n\nI'm looking at the relative speed of 180 km/h. To find the time, I use the formula: time equals distance divided by speed. So, 390 km divided by 180 km/h gives me 13/6 hours, which is 2 hours and 10 minutes. They meet at 6:10 pm. The distance from Paris can be calculated as 80 times (1 plus 13/6), or simply using 80 times 3 and 1/6, which also gives me 253 1/3 km. I’ll provide units for clarity."}]},"output_index":0,"sequence_number":223}

